<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="376" type="reference_group">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,908,1689]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[151,444,908,933]" class="Anthozoa" family="Myriopathidae" genus="Tanacetipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tanacetum">
<emphasis box="[151,444,908,933]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Tanacetipathes tanacetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
colonies consist of a single, bottle-brushed stalk (
<figureCitation box="[1012,1154,908,933]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1158,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanacetipathes tanacetum from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 2 cm), (c) polyps on distal part of primary pinnule under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on distal part of primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1043002/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Figure 7a–b</figureCitation>
). The stem and branches form 4–6 rows of primary pinnules, which are arranged biserially and in alternating groups along the length of the axis. The posterior primary pinnules are generally 1.0– 
<quantity box="[788,867,980,1005]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" unit="cm" value="2.5">2.5 cm</quantity>
in length. The primary pinnules give rise to 2–3 orders of subpinnules, and the secondary pinnules are all mostly arranged uniserially on the abpolypar side of primaries. Tertiary pinnules occur uniserially on abpolypar sides of secondary pinnules, and quaternary pinnules are sometimes present. The skeletal spines are inclined distally and conical to subcylindrical in shape (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1158,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanacetipathes tanacetum from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 2 cm), (c) polyps on distal part of primary pinnule under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on distal part of primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1043002/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Figure 7d– e</figureCitation>
). Spines are smooth or faintly papillose (
<figureCitation box="[663,808,1124,1149]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1158,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanacetipathes tanacetum from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 2 cm), (c) polyps on distal part of primary pinnule under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on distal part of primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1043002/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Figure 7d–e</figureCitation>
). Polypar spines are 190–240 µm in height, whereas abpolypar spines are 120–180 µm in height (
<figureCitation box="[660,775,1160,1185]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1158,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanacetipathes tanacetum from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 2 cm), (c) polyps on distal part of primary pinnule under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on distal part of primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1043002/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Figure 7d</figureCitation>
). The polyps are arranged on a single side of the axis, are typically 
<quantity box="[259,397,1196,1221]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" metricValueMax="9.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" unit="mm" value="0.75" valueMax="0.9" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.9 mm</quantity>
in transverse diameter, and are spaced 
<quantity box="[857,995,1196,1221]" metricMagnitude="-4" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.0" metricValueMax="8.0" metricValueMin="6.0" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" unit="mm" value="0.7" valueMax="0.8" valueMin="0.6">0.6–0.8 mm</quantity>
apart (
<figureCitation box="[1078,1193,1196,1221]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1158,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanacetipathes tanacetum from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 2 cm), (c) polyps on distal part of primary pinnule under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on distal part of primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1043002/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Figure 7c</figureCitation>
). The color of living colonies ranges between brown to light orange (
<figureCitation box="[716,831,1232,1257]" captionStart="FIGURE 7" captionStartId="10.[151,250,1158,1180]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetId="figure@10.[151,1436,267,1136]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURE 7. Tanacetipathes tanacetum from Bermuda showing (a) colonies in situ, (b) preserved specimen (scale bar = 2 cm), (c) polyps on distal part of primary pinnule under light microscopy (scale bar = 2 mm), (d) skeletal spines on distal part of primary pinnule under SEM (scale bar = 100 µm), and (e) close-up of polypar spine under SEM (scale bar = 50 µm)." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/1043002/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Figure 7a</figureCitation>
). Bermudan specimens resemble the 
<typeStatus box="[1268,1371,1232,1257]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1880" class="Anthozoa" family="Myriopathidae" genus="Tanacetipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tanacetum">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">T. tanacetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(see 
<bibRefCitation author="Perez" box="[336,548,1268,1293]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Perez, C. D., Costa, D. L. &amp; Opresko, D. M. (2005) A new species of Tanacetipathes from Brazil, with a redescription of the type species T. tanacetum (Pourtales) (Cnidaria, Anthozoa, Antipatharia). Zootaxa, 890 (1), 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 890.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">
Perez 
<emphasis box="[410,471,1268,1293]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
) in terms of both colony branching pattern and skeletal spine morphology. However, the skeletal spines of Bermudan specimens are substantially larger (range=120–240 µm) than those of the 
<typeStatus box="[193,296,1340,1365]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">lectotype</typeStatus>
of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[335,481,1341,1364]" class="Anthozoa" family="Myriopathidae" genus="Tanacetipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tanacetum">
<emphasis box="[335,481,1341,1364]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">T. tanacetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(range=100–130 µm; 
<bibRefCitation author="Perez" box="[734,936,1340,1365]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Perez, C. D., Costa, D. L. &amp; Opresko, D. M. (2005) A new species of Tanacetipathes from Brazil, with a redescription of the type species T. tanacetum (Pourtales) (Cnidaria, Anthozoa, Antipatharia). Zootaxa, 890 (1), 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 890.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">
Perez 
<emphasis box="[804,861,1340,1365]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens from other locations, including 
<collectingCountry box="[151,222,1376,1401]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Brazil</collectingCountry>
, the Caribbean and Gulf of 
<collectingRegion box="[551,639,1376,1401]" country="Mexico" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">
<collectingCountry box="[551,639,1376,1401]" name="Mexico" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Mexico</collectingCountry>
</collectingRegion>
, with skeletal spines that are up to 300 µm in height have also been assigned to this species (
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[439,681,1412,1437]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Opresko, D. M., Nuttall, M. F. &amp; Hickerson, E. L. (2016) Black corals of the Flower Garden Banks National Marine Sanctuary. Gulf of Mexico Science Science, 2016, 47 - 67." type="journal article" year="2016">
Opresko 
<emphasis box="[546,605,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Perez" box="[696,905,1412,1437]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Perez, C. D., Costa, D. L. &amp; Opresko, D. M. (2005) A new species of Tanacetipathes from Brazil, with a redescription of the type species T. tanacetum (Pourtales) (Cnidaria, Anthozoa, Antipatharia). Zootaxa, 890 (1), 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 890.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">
Perez 
<emphasis box="[768,828,1412,1437]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[919,1225,1412,1437]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Opresko, D. M. &amp; Sanchez, J. A. (2005) Caribbean shallow-water black corals (Cnidaria: Anthozoa: Antipatharia). Caribbean Journal of Science, 41, 492 - 507." type="journal article" year="2005">Opresko &amp; Sanchez, 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Loiola" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Loiola, L. L. &amp; Castro, C. B. (2005) Tanacetipathes Opresko, 2001 (Cnidaria: Antipatharia: Myriopathidae) from Brazil, including two new species. Zootaxa, 1081, 1 - 31. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1081.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Loiola &amp; Castro, 2005</bibRefCitation>
). Consistent with this, we here also assign the Bermudan species to 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[984,1130,1449,1472]" class="Anthozoa" family="Myriopathidae" genus="Tanacetipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tanacetum">
<emphasis box="[984,1130,1449,1472]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">T. tanacetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, despite of it having larger skeletal spines than the 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[419,564,1485,1508]" class="Anthozoa" family="Myriopathidae" genus="Tanacetipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tanacetum">
<emphasis box="[419,564,1485,1508]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">T. tanacetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
lectoype. Future studies should be undertaken, particularly those that include molecular data, in order to determine whether the two forms with different skeletal spine sizes represent different species or intraspecific variability (
<bibRefCitation author="Perez" box="[542,742,1556,1581]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Perez, C. D., Costa, D. L. &amp; Opresko, D. M. (2005) A new species of Tanacetipathes from Brazil, with a redescription of the type species T. tanacetum (Pourtales) (Cnidaria, Anthozoa, Antipatharia). Zootaxa, 890 (1), 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 890.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">
Perez 
<emphasis box="[612,668,1556,1581]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Pourtales" baseAuthorityYear="1880" box="[760,904,1557,1580]" class="Anthozoa" family="Myriopathidae" genus="Tanacetipathes" kingdom="Animalia" order="Antipatharia" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" phylum="Cnidaria" rank="species" species="tanacetum">
<emphasis box="[760,904,1557,1580]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">T. tanacetum</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
has previously been reported from 
<collectingCountry box="[1299,1367,1556,1581]" name="Brazil" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Brazil</collectingCountry>
to the Northwest Atlantic at depths ranging between 
<quantity box="[673,800,1592,1616]" metricMagnitude="2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.565" metricValueMax="12.93" metricValueMin="0.2" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" unit="m" value="656.5" valueMax="1293.0" valueMin="20.0">20–1293 m</quantity>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[814,1041,1592,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Opresko, D. M., Nuttall, M. F. &amp; Hickerson, E. L. (2016) Black corals of the Flower Garden Banks National Marine Sanctuary. Gulf of Mexico Science Science, 2016, 47 - 67." type="journal article" year="2016">
Opresko 
<emphasis box="[918,975,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
2016
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[1053,1221,1592,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Opresko, D. M. (2009) Antipatharia (Cnidaria) of the Gulf of Mexico. In: Tunnell, J. W. Jr., Felder, D. L. &amp; Earle, S. A. (Eds.), Gulf of Mexico origin, waters, and biota. Vol. 1. Biodiversity. Texas A &amp; M University Press, Corpus Christi, 359 - 363." type="book chapter" year="2009">Opresko, 2009</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Perez" box="[1232,1432,1592,1617]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Perez, C. D., Costa, D. L. &amp; Opresko, D. M. (2005) A new species of Tanacetipathes from Brazil, with a redescription of the type species T. tanacetum (Pourtales) (Cnidaria, Anthozoa, Antipatharia). Zootaxa, 890 (1), 1 - 12. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 890.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">
Perez 
<emphasis box="[1302,1358,1592,1617]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 2005
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Loiola" box="[151,419,1628,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Loiola, L. L. &amp; Castro, C. B. (2005) Tanacetipathes Opresko, 2001 (Cnidaria: Antipatharia: Myriopathidae) from Brazil, including two new species. Zootaxa, 1081, 1 - 31. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 1081.1.1" type="journal article" year="2005">Loiola &amp; Castro, 2005</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Padilla" box="[435,686,1628,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Padilla, C. &amp; Lara, M. (2003) Banco Chinchorro: the last shelter for black coral in the Mexican Caribbean. Bulletin of Marine Science, 73, 197 - 202." type="journal article" year="2003">Padilla &amp; Lara, 2003</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Cairns" box="[702,924,1628,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Cairns, S. D., Opresko, D. M. &amp; Hopkins, T. S. (1993) New records of deep-water Cnidaria (Scleractinia &amp; Antipatharia) from the Gulf of Mexico. Northeast Gulf Science, 13, 1 - 11." type="journal article" year="1993">
Cairns 
<emphasis box="[786,847,1628,1653]" italics="true" pageId="9" pageNumber="376">et al.</emphasis>
, 1993
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Opresko" box="[940,1113,1628,1653]" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" refString="Opresko, D. M. (1972) Redescriptions and reevaluations of the antipatharians described by L. F. de Pourtales. Bulletin of Marine Science, 22, 950 - 1017." type="journal article" year="1972">Opresko, 1972</bibRefCitation>
). The Bermudan specimens examined as part of this study were collected at depths between 
<quantity box="[870,969,1664,1689]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.55" metricValueMax="9.6" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="9" pageNumber="376" unit="m" value="75.5" valueMax="96.0" valueMin="55.0">55–96 m</quantity>
(
<tableCitation box="[983,1067,1664,1689]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[151,239,440,463]" captionText="TABLE 1. Black coral specimens examined as part of this study (BAMZ = Bermuda Aquarium, Museum and Zoo; NR = not reported; * = new record for Bermuda)." pageId="9" pageNumber="376">Table 1</tableCitation>
).
</paragraph>
